---
import ArcDocsDiagram from './ArcDocsDiagram'
import { relayArchitectureDiagram } from '../lib/relay-architecture-diagram'
---

<section class="relay-architecture-hero mb-10 rounded-[var(--radius-lg)] border border-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-surface)] p-4 md:p-5" data-pagefind-ignore>
  <div class="relay-architecture-hero__header mb-4 flex flex-wrap items-center justify-between gap-3">
    <div>
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold tracking-tight">Any-To-Any Agent Communication</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="max-w-md text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">
      Surfaces feed a shared runtime. That runtime persists canonical state, routes work to active agents, and links out to peer runtimes on other machines.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="relay-architecture-hero__frame overflow-hidden rounded-[calc(var(--radius-lg)-6px)] border border-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-surface-muted)] p-2 md:p-3">
    <div class="relay-architecture-hero__canvas">
      <ArcDocsDiagram client:load data={relayArchitectureDiagram} />
    </div>
  </div>

  <p class="relay-architecture-hero__hint mt-3 text-xs leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">
    This is the system in one loop: surfaces feed the runtime, the runtime persists shared state, and work can route to local agents or peer runtimes on other machines.
  </p>
</section>
